  "prompt": "Why do cats spit hairballs? Is it harmful?",
  "response": "Cats spit up hairballs as a natural way to remove hair they've ingested while grooming themselves. Here are some key points about hairballs:\n\nWhy cats produce hairballs:\n1. Cats constantly groom themselves using their tongue\n2. Their tongue has tiny barbs that collect loose hair\n3. Most hair passes through the digestive system normally\n4. Sometimes hair accumulates in the stomach and forms a hairball\n\nAre hairballs harmful?\n1. Occasional hairballs are normal and not usually dangerous\n2. Frequent hairballs might indicate:\n- Excessive grooming\n- Skin problems\n- Digestive issues\n\nPotential concerns:\n1. Large hairballs can cause intestinal blockages\n2. Repeated vomiting can lead to dehydration\n3. Persistent hairball issues may require veterinary attention\n\nHow to reduce hairballs:\n1. Regular brushing to remove loose hair\n2. Special hairball-control cat food\n3. Supplements that help hair pass through digestive system\n4. Keeping cats hydrated\n5. Addressing underlying health issues\n\nWhile hairballs are generally normal, excessive or frequent hairballs should be discussed with a veterinarian.",
